rship for Filipino Catholics in Manitoba, to home chapels, and healing traditions, Marshall explores the day-to-day celebrations of bayanihan, or communal spirit. Drawing on experiences from Manitoba’s Filipino population, Bayanihan and Belonging reveals that religious practise fulfills not only a need for spiritual guidance, but also for community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFilipino AmericansxReligion. 0aFilipino AmericansxSocial life and customs. 0aFilipinoszCanadaxReligion. 0aFilipinoszCanadaxSocial life and customs. 0aFilipinoszCanada. 0aFilipinoszManitobaxReligion. 0aFilipinoszManitobaxSocial life and customs. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751751940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487517519423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487517519/original  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  aGBV-deGruyter-alles